Description¶

(AI generated image, I used Stable Diffution's DreamStudio "Prompt: red virus cells growing on a medieval book, getting eaten by an iPhone , dreamy state, 8k, super detailed")

The coronavirus took the entire world by surprise, changing everyone's daily routine. City dwellers no longer spent their free time outside, going to cafes and malls; more people were home, reading books. That attracted the attention of startups that rushed to develop new apps for book lovers.

I've been given a database of one of the services competing in this market. It contains data on books, publishers, authors, and customer ratings and reviews of books. This information will be used to generate a value proposition for a new product.

Description of the data :

books:

Contains data on books:

book_id

author_id

title

num_pages — number of pages

publication_date

publisher_id

authors:

Contains data on authors:

author_id

author

publishers:

Contains data on publishers:

publisher_id

publisher

ratings:

Contains data on user ratings:

rating_id

book_id

username — the name of the user who rated the book

rating

reviews:

Contains data on customer reviews:

review_id

book_id

username — the name of the user who reviewed the book

text — the text of the review

The goal of the study¶

Generate information for making a value proposition for a new product.

Query Points¶

points that I belive will help the Startup in getting valuebale Insights

  • the number of books released after January 1, 2000.
  • the number of user reviews and the average rating for each book.
  • the publisher that has released the greatest number of books with more than 50 pages (this will help excluding brochures and similar publications from the analysis).
  • the author with the highest average book rating (books with at least 50 ratings).
  • the average number of text reviews among users who rated more than 50 books.

the number of user reviews and the average rating for each book¶

In [11]:
avg_rating = ''' SELECT b.title, COUNT( review_id) as review_count, AVG(rating) as avg_rating
                FROM books b
                INNER JOIN ratings ON ratings.book_id = b.book_id
                INNER JOIN reviews ON reviews.book_id = ratings.book_id 
                GROUP BY title
                ORDER BY review_count DESC,avg_rating ASC  '''
query(avg_rating)

the publisher that has released the greatest number of books with more than 50 pages¶

In [12]:
publisher_50 = '''SELECT p.publisher, COUNT(b.book_id) as books_count
                  FROM books AS b 
                  INNER JOIN publishers AS p
                  ON b.publisher_id = p.publisher_id and num_pages > 50               
                  GROUP BY publisher
                  ORDER BY books_count DESC
                  LIMIT 1 '''
query(publisher_50)
Out[12]:
publisher books_count
0 Penguin Books 42

the author with the highest average book rating (books with at least 50 ratings)¶

In [9]:
author_50 = ''' SELECT a.author, b.title, AVG (r.rating) avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating_id) AS rating_count
                FROM books AS b 
                INNER JOIN authors AS a
                ON a.author_id = b.author_id
                INNER JOIN ratings AS r 
                ON r.book_id = b.book_id 
                GROUP BY author, title
                HAVING  COUNT(r.rating_id) > 50 
                ORDER BY avg_rating DESC
                limit 1'''
query(author_50)
Out[9]:
author title avg_rating rating_count
0 J.K. Rowling/Mary GrandPré Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (Harr... 4.414634 82

the average number of text reviews among users who rated more than 50 books¶

In [14]:
text_50 = ''' SELECT COUNT(text)/COUNT(DISTINCT username) AS text_review_avg 
              FROM reviews
              WHERE username IN (
              SELECT username
              FROM ratings
              GROUP BY username
              HAVING COUNT(*) > 50)'''
query(text_50)
Out[14]:
text_review_avg
0 24

Conclusion¶

It seems that most books are released after the year 2000, thou most books have pretty high average ratings with 3+ we need to consider the review count alongside average rating to have a decent minimum starting point to be in the suggested books.

As we mentioned before, we want books with over 50 pages so it won't include brochures or similarly short publications. The Publisher “Penguin Books” excel in this “Real book” category, highly advised to include them.

J.K Rowling has the highest average book rating, followed by my own favorite J.R.R. Tolkien, and both share thye same theme of fantasy books, we should point out these type of authors and themes. for a more insightful score a “Critics” section can be beneficial for the reader, we named them Critics as they rated more than 50 Books! where these books also had a lot of text reviews with an average of 24.

All in all, we have a pretty decent starting point for our Product.
